%html#top
  %head
    %meta{:charset => "utf-8"}
      %meta{:content => "width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0", :name => "viewport"}
      %link{:href => "../css/style.css", :rel => "stylesheet", :type => "text/css"}
      %link{:href => "../img/favicon/16x16.png", :rel => "icon", :type => "image/png", :sizes => "16x16"}
      %link{:href => "../img/favicon/32x32.png", :rel => "icon", :type => "image/png", :sizes => "32x32"}
      %link{:href => "../img/favicon/96x96.png", :rel => "icon", :type => "image/png", :sizes => "96x96"}
      %link{:href => "../img/favicon/144x144.png", :rel => "icon", :type => "image/png", :sizes => "144x144"}
      %title The Portfolio of Darko Miladinovikj
  %body
    .wrapper.text-center.back-none
      = Haml::Engine.new(File.read("_header.haml")).render

    %hr

      .wrapper.text-center.back-none
        .row
          .col-12.back-none.folio
            %h2 Remington 1867 Navy Rolling Block Pistol
            /%p I'm a huge fan of 19th century weaponary. Here, I wanted to create a less common 19th century firearm where I replicate the case hardening (blue/brown colory stuff) on the metal while keeping in mind the process behind it. Triangle count is at around 3000 and it uses 1024x1024 texture sheets (diffuse, specular, normal & gloss). Rendered in Marmoset Toolbag 2.
        .row
          .col-12.back-none.folio
            %img{:src => "../img/rollingblock/01.jpg"}
            %img{:src => "../img/rollingblock/02.jpg"}
            %img{:src => "../img/rollingblock/03.jpg"}
            %img{:src => "../img/rollingblock/04.jpg"}
            %img{:src => "../img/rollingblock/05.jpg"}
            %img{:src => "../img/rollingblock/06.jpg"}
            %img{:src => "../img/rollingblock/07.jpg"}
            %img{:src => "../img/rollingblock/08.jpg"}
            %img{:src => "../img/rollingblock/09.jpg"}
            %img{:src => "../img/rollingblock/10.jpg"}


    = Haml::Engine.new(File.read("_footer.haml")).render
